    "text": "Erdős Problem #450: declared status 'open'. Formalized: no. How large must $y=y(\\epsilon,n)$ be such that the number of integers in $(x,x+y)$ with a divisor in $(n,2n)$ is at most $\\epsilon y$? Current best: On the other hand, Cambie has observed that if $\\epsilon\\ll 1/n$ then $y(\\epsilon,n)\\sim 2n$: indeed, if $y<2n$ then this is impossible taking $x+n$ to be a multiple of the lowest common multiple of $\\{n+1,\\ldots,2n-1\\}$. Prize: no. Tags: divisors, number theory.",
